-- в”Ђв”Ђ Wufoo в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Wufoo is an online form builder owned by Momentive (SurveyMonkey) that lets teams create web forms, surveys, and payment forms using drag-and-drop fields, conditional logic, and ready-made templates.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$freemium$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free plan available; paid plans from $16.25/month billed annually (Starter)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2006, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Subsidiary of Momentive (SurveyMonkey)$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Tampa, Florida (parent company Momentive headquartered in San Mateo, California)$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Wufoo Review 2026: Pricing, Features and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Wufoo is a drag-and-drop online form builder from SurveyMonkey. See pricing plans from free to 210 dollars a month, key features, and who it is best for.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Wufoo is an online form-building platform founded in 2006 in Tampa, Florida by Kevin Hale, Chris Campbell, and Ryan Campbell as a Y Combinator-backed startup. It was one of the earliest widely adopted web-based form builders, letting non-developers create contact forms, registration forms, surveys, and payment forms through a drag-and-drop interface rather than writing HTML. SurveyMonkey (now operating as Momentive) acquired Wufoo in 2011 for approximately 35 million dollars, and Wufoo continues to operate as a distinct product and brand within Momentive's portfolio alongside SurveyMonkey itself. The platform's core strengths are its form logic and payment integrations. Conditional logic lets builders show or hide fields, skip users to different pages, and configure up to 50 form rules based on prior answers, which supports more complex use cases like multi-branch intake forms or qualification surveys. Wufoo integrates with major payment processors, including Stripe, PayPal, Braintree, Authorize.Net, Chargify, USA ePay, and FreshBooks, allowing forms to directly collect payments, donations, or order details. Users can start from over 400 pre-built templates spanning registration, feedback, event, and order forms rather than building from scratch. Wufoo's pricing follows a tiered subscription model with a genuinely usable free plan (5 forms, 100 entries, 10 fields, 1 user). Paid tiers scale by number of forms, monthly entries, API requests, file storage, and team seats: Starter at 16.25 dollars per month (billed annually) removes the field cap and adds file uploads and integrations; Professional at 33.25 dollars per month adds payment acceptance, higher file limits, and field encryption; Advanced and Ultimate tiers extend entry volumes up to 200,000 per month and support up to 60 users for larger organizations. Wufoo is best suited for small businesses, nonprofits, and teams that need reliable, no-code forms with strong conditional logic and payment collection, without the more modern AI-assisted or highly customizable design features found in newer builders like Typeform, Jotform, or Paperform. Its long operating history and backing by Momentive give it stability, though its interface and feature pace have been widely noted by reviewers as more dated than newer entrants in the category.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '106def15-bc26-47dd-b9c7-dbb691ff1a8c';

