-- в”Ђв”Ђ Xero в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Xero is a cloud-based accounting software platform for small and mid-sized businesses, offering invoicing, bank reconciliation, and reporting alongside a large third-party app marketplace.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$subscription$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$From $25/month (Early plan, US pricing)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2006, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$approximately 6,200 employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Wellington, New Zealand$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Xero Review 2026: Pricing Plans and Features for Small Business$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Xero offers cloud accounting for small businesses with plans from 25 dollars a month. Compare Early, Growing, and Established plans, features, and alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Xero is a cloud-based accounting software platform founded in 2006 in Wellington, New Zealand, where the company remains headquartered today. Xero went public on the New Zealand Exchange in 2007 and later moved its primary listing to the Australian Securities Exchange in 2012, growing into one of the most widely used accounting platforms for small and mid-sized businesses, with roughly 6,200 employees across offices in Australia, New Zealand, the United Kingdom, the United States, Canada, Singapore, and South Africa. The platform centers on giving small business owners real-time visibility into their finances through automated bank feeds that pull in transactions for reconciliation, online invoicing with payment tracking, expense and bill management, and financial reporting dashboards. Xero is built as a multi-user, cloud-native application accessible from web browsers and mobile apps on iOS and Android, which lets business owners, bookkeepers, and accountants collaborate on the same live set of books rather than exchanging file backups. One of Xero's most cited strengths is its app marketplace, which connects to more than 700 third-party business applications spanning payroll, payments, inventory, CRM, and industry-specific tools, letting businesses extend Xero's core accounting functionality without switching platforms. Xero's US pricing is structured around three subscription tiers. Early, at 25 dollars per month, is capped at 20 invoices and 5 bills monthly, aimed at freelancers, sole proprietors, and very early-stage businesses. Growing, at 55 dollars per month, removes those invoice and bill caps and adds customizable dashboards and financial health scorecards, fitting most growing small businesses. Established, at 90 dollars per month, adds multi-currency accounting, project tracking, expense claims, and deeper analytics such as 180-day cash flow forecasting, and becomes necessary once a business needs any of those capabilities. All three tiers include unlimited users at no extra cost, a notable difference from accounting competitors that charge per seat. Xero frequently runs new-customer promotions, such as steep percentage discounts for the first several months, that reduce the effective starting price before regular billing applies. Xero is best suited for small businesses and the accounting or bookkeeping firms that serve them, particularly those that value a large integration ecosystem and collaborative, real-time bookkeeping over deep enterprise-grade financial controls found in larger ERP systems.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'ab58553d-75b9-40f6-9b54-61fbab218754';

